The Stallion Empowerment Initiative (SEI), the charity arm of Stallion Group, has partnered with Morsun Mobile Clinic to offer free medical consultation and drugs to residents of Lagos in 11 clinics. The group’s CEO, Mr. Anant Badjatya, said the affiliation would treat over 70 common ailments prevalent in Nigeria and would reach over 20,000 people in the city over the course of two months. He said, “There is nothing greater than the safety of the people of this country; and it is our responsibility to support the government and the community in this time of need.” The service aims to provide succour to people who cannot access hospitals due to overcrowding during the pandemic or for those who cannot simply afford treatment. Dear valued readers, subscribe to the Daily Trust e-paper to continue enjoying our diet of authoritative news. Kindly subscribe here According to the group, associating with the mobile clinic is a step towards the fulfillment of accessible healthcare and wellbeing of the community. Stallion is working in close coordination with all stakeholders and the government to alleviate the circumstances of COVID-19 patients, frontline workers and lots of daily wage earners who are most impacted by the lockdown. It would be recalled that the group’s charity arm, SEI, pledged free rice and fish for three months to all hospitals dedicated to COVID-19 care in Nigeria. 89 state hospitals in Nigeria are already registered as part of the programme. Stallion provides free food items to COVID-19 treatment centres Clinics with nothing: How millions meant for the sick are never spent Stallion commences free service clinic for VWs, Audi, Skoda